.TH "DISPOSABLESTACK.ADOPT" "3JS" "July 30, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
DisposableStack.adopt \- DisposableStack.prototype.adopt()
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]adopt()\f[B]\f[R] method of \f[CR]DisposableStack\f[R]
instances registers a value that doesn\(cqt implement the disposable
protocol to the stack by providing a custom disposer function.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
adopt(value, onDispose)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]value\f[R]
Any value to be registered to the stack.
.TP
\f[B]onDispose\f[R]
A function that will be called when the stack is disposed.
The function receives \f[CR]value\f[R] as its only argument.
.SS Return value
The same \f[CR]value\f[R] that was passed in.
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]TypeError\f[R]
Thrown if \f[CR]onDispose\f[R] is not a function.
.TP
\f[B]ReferenceError\f[R]
Thrown if the stack is already disposed.
.SH DESCRIPTION
The primary purpose of \f[CR]adopt()\f[R] is to register a value that
doesn\(cqt implement the disposable protocol to the stack.
If the value is already disposable, you can use \f[CR]use()\f[R]
instead, which automatically uses the value\(cqs
\f[CR][Symbol.dispose]()\f[R] method as the disposer.
.PP
\f[CR]adopt(value, onDispose)\f[R] is almost the same as
\f[CR]defer(() => onDispose(value))\f[R], but it allows you to declare
the resource and register it on the same line.
This way, there\(cqs minimal chance of an error happening between the
resource creation and registration, which will cause the resource to
leak.
.PP
\f[B]Good\f[R]
.IP
.EX
using disposer = \f[B]new\f[R] DisposableStack();
\f[B]const\f[R] reader = disposer.adopt(stream.getReader(), (reader) \f[B]=>\f[R]
  reader.releaseLock(),
);
.EE
.PP
\f[B]Bad\f[R]
.IP
.EX
using disposer = \f[B]new\f[R] DisposableStack();
\f[B]const\f[R] reader = stream.getReader();
\f[I]// If someone adds code in between these lines and an error occurs,\f[R]
\f[I]// the stream will be locked forever.\f[R]
disposer.defer(() \f[B]=>\f[R] reader.close());
.EE
.PP
In the same spirit of \(lqmake your resource registered as soon as
it\(cqs declared\(rq, you should always wrap your resource acquisition
expression in \f[CR]adopt()\f[R], instead of extracting it to a separate
statement.
.PP
\f[B]Bad\f[R]
.IP
.EX
using disposer = \f[B]new\f[R] DisposableStack();
\f[B]const\f[R] reader = stream.getReader();
disposer.adopt(reader, (reader) \f[B]=>\f[R] reader.close());
.EE
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using adopt()
This code consumes a \f[CR]ReadableStream\f[R] via a
\f[CR]ReadableStreamDefaultReader\f[R].
The reader does not implement the disposable protocol, so we use
\f[CR]adopt()\f[R] to register it to the stack.
.IP
.EX
{
  using disposer = \f[B]new\f[R] DisposableStack();
  \f[B]const\f[R] reader = disposer.adopt(stream.getReader(), (reader) \f[B]=>\f[R]
    reader.releaseLock(),
  );
  \f[B]const\f[R] { value, done } = reader.read();
  \f[B]if\f[R] (!done) {
    \f[I]// Process the value\f[R]
  }
  \f[I]// The reader.releaseLock() method is called here before exiting\f[R]
}
.EE
